<td class="mbox-text" style="">It has been suggested that <i><a href="/wiki/Threshold_consciousness" title="Threshold consciousness">Threshold consciousness</a></i> be <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Merging_and_moving_pages" title="Wikipedia:Merging and moving pages" class="mw-redirect">merged</a> into this article or section. (<a href="/wiki/Talk:Hypnagogia" title="Talk:Hypnagogia">Discuss</a>)</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Hypnagogia</b> (<a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title="Ancient Greek">Greek</a> ὕπνος, <i>húpnos</i> "sleep" + the <a href="/wiki/Root_(linguistics)" title="Root (linguistics)">root</a> found in ἄγω, <i>ágō</i> "to lead away, conduct, convey", ἀγωγεύς, <i>agōgeús</i> "conveyor", ἀγωγή, <i>agōgḗ</i> "abduction, transport, leading away" etc.), often misspelled <i>hypnogaia</i> or <i>hypnogogia</i>, is a term coined by <a href="/wiki/Louis_Ferdinand_Alfred_Maury" title="Louis Ferdinand Alfred Maury">Alfred Maury</a> for the transitional state between <a href="/wiki/Wakefulness" title="Wakefulness">wakefulness</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sleep" title="Sleep">sleep</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
